{"timestamp": "2025-12-05 15:43:05.985466", "event": "llm_start", "messages": "content='Based on the diagnosis report: Troubleshooting diagnosis report — network health assessment\\n\\nSummary\\n- Overall the backbone and server plane are healthy: OSPF runs on core and server routers, server subnet (10.200.0.0/24) is advertised and reachable, DNS/DHCP/web/load‑balancer hosts respond to pings, and the majority of host → server reachability tests succeeded with no loss.\\n- Two anomalies were identified and localized:\\n  1. A single access host (host_1_1_1_1) has no IP address and is unable to reach the network.\\n  2. The distribution router for the 10.1.1.0/24 segment (router_dist_1_1) appears to have FRR/OSPF daemons unreachable — FRR control-plane is not responding to queries.\\n\\nEvidence and findings (captured outputs)\\n1) Host host_1_1_1_1 — isolated / no IP\\n- get_host_net_config(host_1_1_1_1)\\n  - eth0 present and UP but no inet/IPv4 address configured (ifconfig shows no \"inet\" line for eth0; ip addr shows eth0 but no assigned address).\\n- ping_pair(host_1_1_1_1 -> web_server_2) and (host_1_1_1_1 -> host_2_2_1_1))\\n  - Both returned: \"ping: connect: Network is unreachable\".\\n- In the reachability scan, tests sourced from host_1_1_1_1 were marked \"unknown\" (no successful tests reported).\\n- Interpretation: host_1_1_1_1 is not DHCP‑leased (or otherwise not configured) and therefore cannot reach anywhere beyond its local interface.\\n\\n2) router_dist_1_1 — FRR/OSPF control-plane problem\\n- frr_get_ospf_conf(router_dist_1_1) returned: \"Exiting: failed to connect to any daemons.\"\\n  - This indicates the FRR daemons (zebra/ospfd/etc.) are not responding to management queries or not running.\\n- get_host_net_config(router_dist_1_1) shows the router\\'s interfaces and bridge are configured:\\n  - br0: 10.1.1.1/24 (present)\\n  - eth0: 172.16.0.7/31 (connected toward core)\\n  - Interfaces are UP and packets counters show activity.\\n- Core routers’ OSPF and route tables do NOT list 10.1.1.0/24 in their OSPF routes (no O‑route for 10.1.1.0/24 in the core router outputs).\\n  - This indicates the 10.1.1.0/24 prefix is not being advertised into OSPF (consistent with FRR not running on router_dist_1_1).\\n- Interpretation: although the distribution router has local interfaces configured, its FRR control-plane is unavailable, so its connected networks (10.1.1.0/24) are not being announced into OSPF and won\\'t be reachable from other areas/routers.\\n\\n3) Overall backbone / server plane — healthy\\n- frr_get_ospf_conf and frr_show_ip_route on router_core_1, router_core_2, router_core_3, and server_access_router show:\\n  - OSPF adjacencies are present with peers and multiple areas; SPF has run recently.\\n  - Routes to 10.200.0.0/24 and host subnets 10.1.2.0/24, 10.2.1.0/24, 10.2.2.0/24 exist and are being propagated across cores.\\n- reachability tests:\\n  - dhcp_server, dns_server, web_server_{0..3}, load_balancer and many host pairs successfully pinged web_server_2 and other hosts with 0% loss and reasonable RTTs.\\n- Interpretation: central services (DHCP, DNS, web, load‑balancer) and the core/distribution paths other than the 10.1.1.0/24 segment are operating normally.\\n\\nImpact / scope\\n- Immediate impact: host_1_1_1_1 is isolated (no IPv4) and cannot reach servers or other subnets.\\n- Broader impact: Any hosts in 10.1.1.0/24 (the access segment served by router_dist_1_1) may not be reachable from other areas because 10.1.1.0/24 is not advertised into OSPF while FRR on router_dist_1_1 is non-responsive. If other hosts in that VLAN have addresses, they could be locally reachable to one another but unreachable from the rest of the network and possibly unable to obtain DHCP leases if relay/forwarding requires the distribution router to be fully functional.\\n- Non-impacted areas: server farm (10.200.0.0/24), load balancer, DNS, DHCP, and other host subnets shown in route tables are reachable and functioning.\\n\\nProbable root causes\\n- host_1_1_1_1: Likely failed to obtain DHCP lease (DHCP client issue on host or switch port misconfiguration). Evidence: NIC is up but no IPv4 address; attempts to ping fail with \"Network is unreachable.\"\\n- router_dist_1_1: FRR daemons not running or not accessible (zebra/ospfd not responding), causing failure to advertise 10.1.1.0/24 into OSPF. Evidence: frr_get_ospf_conf failed with daemon connection error, while the router still has local interface configuration and link-level connectivity.\\n\\nAdditional notes / suggested follow-up checks (diagnostic, not remediation)\\n- On host_1_1_1_1: check DHCP client status/logs (dhclient/NetworkManager) and switch port VLAN membership; verify whether other hosts in same access segment have addresses.\\n- On router_dist_1_1: check FRR service status (is zebra/ospfd running?), review FRR logs, and inspect OSPF neighbor status and LSA generation for the 10.1.1.0/24 network.\\n- Verify whether DHCP relay (if used on router_dist_1_1) is running and able to forward requests to the central DHCP server.\\n- Confirm whether any other devices in 10.1.1.0/24 are similarly impacted (to assess scope).\\n\\nConclusion\\n- The network core and server plane are healthy and delivering services properly.\\n- Two localized issues explain the observed anomalies:\\n  1) host_1_1_1_1 has no IPv4 and is isolated (host-level DHCP/configuration issue).\\n  2) router_dist_1_1’s FRR control-plane is not responding, preventing 10.1.1.0/24 from being advertised in OSPF (control-plane fault on that distribution router).\\n- These issues are localized (one host and one distribution router); they account for the loss of reachability for the 10.1.1.0/24 segment and the specific isolated host observed.\\n\\nIf you want, I can run the next diagnostic checks (service status on router_dist_1_1 FRR, DHCP client status on host_1_1_1_1, check whether other 10.1.1.x hosts have leases) to further confirm the root causes., please provide the submission. Do not submit if no report available.' additional_kwargs={} response_metadata={} id='da3fdd02-a79b-4f9e-815e-52c90aa67d68'", "model": {"lc": 1, "type": "constructor", "id": ["langchain", "chat_models", "openai", "ChatOpenAI"], "kwargs": {"model_name": "gpt-5-mini", "openai_api_key": {"lc": 1, "type": "secret", "id": ["OPENAI_API_KEY"]}, "stream_usage": true}, "name": "ChatOpenAI"}}
